quran[23]{c,v,t,f}:
  88,25,"Surely to Us is their return;"
  88,26,"and then it is for Us to call them to account."
  89,22,"and when your Lord appears{1} with rows upon rows of angels,",footnotes:1:Although literally the words jaa Rabbuka mean your Lord will come
  89,23,"and when Hell is brought near that Day. On that Day will man understand, but of what avail will that understanding be?{1}",footnotes:1:The words in the original can have two meanings:
  89,24,"He will say: “Would that I had sent ahead what would be of avail for this life of mine!”"
  90,16,"or to a destitute lying in dust;{1}",footnotes:1:Since in the foregoing verses the extravagances of man which he indulges in for ostentation and expression of superiority to others
  90,17,"and, then besides this, he be one of those who believed,{1} and enjoined upon one another steadfastness and enjoined upon one another compassion.{2}",footnotes:1:[That is, in addition to these qualities it is essential that one should be a believer, for without faith no act is an act of virtue, nor acceptable in the sight of Allah. At numerous places in the Quran it has been stated that only such an act of virtue is appreciable and becomes a means of salvation as is accompanied by faith. In Surah An-Nisa, for example, it has been said: The one who does good deeds, whether man or woman, provided that the one is a believer, will enter Paradise (verse 124). In Surah An-Nahl: Whosoever does righteous deeds, whether male or female, provided that he is a believer, We shall surely grant him to live a pure life in this world, and We will reward such people (in the Hereafter) according to their best deeds (verse 97). In Surah Al-Momin: Whoever does good, whether man or woman, provided that he is a believer, all such people shall enter Paradise wherein they shall be provided without measure. (verse 4). Whoever studies the Quran, will see that in this Book wherever the good reward of a righteous act has been mentioned, it has always been made conditional upon the faith, a good act without faith has nowhere been regarded as acceptable to God, nor has any hope been given for a reward for it.],footnotes:2:[Here, the following important point should also not remain hidden from view: In this verse it has not been said: Then he believed, but: Then being among those who have believed. This means that mere believing as an individual and remaining content with it is not what is desired; what is desired is that every new believer should join those who have already believed so as to form a party of the believers, to bring about a believing society, which should work for establishing the virtues and wiping out the vices as demanded by the faith.]
  90,18,"These are the People of the Right Hand."
  91,13,"Then Allah's Messenger warned them: “Hands off the she-camel and her drink!”{1}",footnotes:1:At other places in the Quran the following details
  91,14,"But they rejected his statement as a lie and hamstrung the she-camel.{1} For that crime their Lord rumbled down upon them, utterly razing them to the ground.",footnotes:1:According to (Surah Al-Aaraf, Ayat 77), after they had killed the she-camel, the people of Thamud said to the Prophet Salih (peace be upon him): Bring the scourge with which you threatened us. And according to Surah Houd, Ayat 65, the Prophet Salih (peace be upon him) said to them: Well, you have only three more days to enjoy yourselves in your houses. This is a limit that will not prove false.
  91,15,"He has no fear of its sequel.{1}",footnotes:1:That is, Allah is not like the kings of the world and the rulers of governments, who, when they want to take some action against a people, are compelled to consider what will be the consequences of their action. Allah’s power is supreme. He had no apprehension that some supporting power of the Thamud would come out to avenge itself on Him.
  92,10,"We shall facilitate for him the way to Hardship,{1}",footnotes:1:This way has been called the hard way
  92,11,"and his wealth shall be of no avail to him when he perishes.{1}",footnotes:1:In other words it means that he has to die one day and leave behind in the world whatever he had amassed for his ease and enjoyment. If he did not earn and send forward something for the Hereafter
  92,12,"Surely it is for Us to show the Right Way,{1}",footnotes:1:That is, Allah as the Creator of man has on the basis of His wisdom, His justice and His mercy, taken on Himself the responsibility not to leave him uninformed in the world, but to tell him what is the right way and what are the wrong ways, what is good and what is evil, what is lawful and what is unlawful, what attitude and conduct will make him an obedient servant and what attitude and conduct will make him a disobedient servant. This same thing has been expressed in Surah An-Nahl, thus: Allah has taken upon Himself to show the right way, when there are also crooked ways.    (verse 9 Also see E.N. 9 of Surah An-Nahl).
  93,7,"Did He not find you unaware of the Right Way, and then directed you to it?{1}",footnotes:1:The word daallan as used in the original is derived from
  93,8,"And did He not find you in want, and then enriched you?{1}",footnotes:1:The Prophet’s (peace be upon him) father had left only a
  93,9,"Therefore, be not harsh with the orphan;{1}",footnotes:1:That is, as you yourself have been an orphan and Allah
  94,4,"And did We not exalt your fame?{1}",footnotes:1:This was said at a time when no one could even conceive how the renown of the one unique individual
  94,5,"Indeed, there is ease with hardship."
  94,6,"Most certainly, there is ease with hardship.{1}",footnotes:1:This has been repeated twice so as to reassure the Prophet (peace be upon him) that the bad times he was passing through at that time would not last for ever
  95,1,"By the fig and the olive;{1}",footnotes:1:There has been much difference of opinion among the commentators about the explanation of this verse. Hasan Basri
  95,2,"and by the Mount Sinai,{1}",footnotes:1:The words in the original are Tur-i-Sinin. Sinin is another name for the Sinai Peninsula. It is called Saina or Sina as well as Sinin. In the Quran itself at one place the words Tur-i-Sinin have been used. Since the land in which Mt. Sinai is located is well known as Sina
  95,3,"and by this city (of Makkah), a haven of peace:"
